The year-on-year CPI reading was the lowest since December 2010, when the rate was 3.5% JOHANNESBURG - South Africaâ€™s headline consumer price inflation slowed to 3.6% year-on-year in November, from 3.7% in October, data from Statistics South Africa showed on Wednesday. The year-on-year CPI reading was the lowest since December 2010, when the rate was 3.5%, the statistics agency said. On a month-on-month basis, price growth was 0.1%, versus 0.0% in the previous month. Core inflation, which excludes prices of food, non-alcoholic beverages, petrol and energy, slowed to 3.9% year-on-year in November compared with 4% in October, while on a month-on-month basis was at 0.1%, the same as in the prior month.